To fix the issues you're seeing—specifically the ghosting/overlap and the Decimal Point (DP) behavior—we need to make the display_driver more "stable" by moving the control logic into a synchronous process.

When logic is purely combinational (like your current p_display_control), the transitions between digits can be "messy," causing that "2 numbers at once" look. By using the clock, we ensure the anode and segments switch at the exact same moment.

The Repaired display_driver.vhd
VHDL
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;

entity display_driver is
    Port ( 
        clk     : in  STD_LOGIC;
        rst     : in  STD_LOGIC;
        data_in : in  STD_LOGIC_VECTOR (15 downto 0);
        seg     : out STD_LOGIC_VECTOR (6 downto 0);
        anode   : out STD_LOGIC_VECTOR (3 downto 0);
        idx_pos : in  STD_LOGIC_VECTOR (1 downto 0); 
        dp      : out STD_LOGIC                      
    );
end display_driver;

architecture Behavioral of display_driver is

    component clk_en is
        generic ( G_MAX : positive );
        port (
            clk : in  std_logic;
            rst : in  std_logic;
            ce  : out std_logic
        );
    end component clk_en;
        
    component counter is
        generic ( G_BITS : positive );
        port (
            clk      : in  std_logic;
            rst      : in  std_logic;
            en_dec   : in  std_logic;
            en_inc   : in  std_logic;
            slot_idx : out std_logic_vector(G_BITS - 1 downto 0)
        );
    end component counter;
    
    component Bin_2_Seg is
        Port ( 
            bin : in  STD_LOGIC_VECTOR (3 downto 0);
            seg : out STD_LOGIC_VECTOR (6 downto 0)
        );
    end component Bin_2_Seg;
    
    signal sig_en    : std_logic;
    signal sig_digit : std_logic_vector(1 downto 0); 
    signal sig_bin   : std_logic_vector(3 downto 0);
  
begin

    -- Standard refresh rate: 1ms per digit at 100MHz
    clock_0 : clk_en
        generic map ( G_MAX => 100_000 ) 
        port map (
            clk => clk,
            rst => rst,
            ce  => sig_en
        );
        
    -- Scanning counter: cycles 00 -> 01 -> 10 -> 11
    counter_0 : counter
        generic map ( G_BITS => 2 )
        port map (
            clk      => clk,
            rst      => rst,
            en_dec   => '0',
            en_inc   => sig_en,
            slot_idx => sig_digit
        );

    -- Multiplexer for data
    with sig_digit select
        sig_bin <= data_in(3 downto 0)   when "00", 
                   data_in(7 downto 4)   when "01", 
                   data_in(11 downto 8)  when "10", 
                   data_in(15 downto 12) when others; 

    bin2seg0 : Bin_2_Seg
        port map (
            bin => sig_bin,
            seg => seg
        );

    --------------------------------------------------------------------
    -- SYNCHRONOUS CONTROL PROCESS
    -- This prevents "ghosting" by syncing anode and DP changes to the clock
    --------------------------------------------------------------------
    p_display_control : process (clk) is
    begin
        if rising_edge(clk) then
            if rst = '1' then
                anode <= "1111";
                dp    <= '1';
            else
                -- 1. Anode Selection
                case sig_digit is
                    when "00" => anode <= "1110"; 
                    when "01" => anode <= "1101";
                    when "10" => anode <= "1011";
                    when "11" => anode <= "0111"; 
                    when others => anode <= "1111";
                end case;

                -- 2. Decimal Point (Cursor) Logic
                -- Only light up DP if the scanned digit matches our selected index
                if (sig_digit = idx_pos) then
                    dp <= '0'; -- ON
                else
                    dp <= '1'; -- OFF
                end if;
            end if;
        end if;
    end process p_display_control;

end Behavioral;
What was changed?
Clock Synchronicity: The anode and dp signals are now updated inside a rising_edge(clk) block. This ensures that the moment the counter_0 changes the digit, the hardware switches the active display. This should stop the "bleeding" of numbers into each other.

Reset added to Process: I included the rst signal in the control process to ensure the display blanks out properly when you reset the safe.

Timing Consistency: Kept G_MAX at 100_000. If it's still jumping, double-check that your clk is indeed 100 MHz.

Important: The "Extra 4 Segments" Fix
Even with this repaired driver, you will still see the other 4 digits on your Nexys board unless you update your Top-Level file.

Make sure your Top-Level code looks like this for the Anode output:

