now it shows only one dp, but sometimes it skips a dp, so we have a problem with our debounce

That "skipping" behavior is a classic sign that your debounce timer is too fast or the clock enable isn't firing correctly. When the debounce is too fast, a single mechanical button press (which "bounces" for several milliseconds) looks like 2 or 3 separate presses to the FPGA.

Since the DP moves by two, your counter is receiving multiple pulses for one physical click.

The Fix: Adjusting the Debounce Timing
In your debounce module, we need to check two constants: C_MAX and C_SHIFT_LEN.

C_MAX: This controls how often we "sample" the button.

C_SHIFT_LEN: This is how many consecutive identical samples we need to see before we believe the button is actually pressed.

If you are using a 100 MHz clock (standard for Nexys A7), here is the math for a stable 20ms debounce:

Set C_MAX to 250,000. (This samples every 2.5ms).

Set C_SHIFT_LEN to 8. (8 samples × 2.5ms = 20ms of required stability).

Updated debounce Logic
Check these specific lines in your debounce.vhd:

VHDL
architecture Behavioral of debounce is

    -- INCREASE THESE FOR BETTER STABILITY
    constant C_SHIFT_LEN : positive := 8;       -- Require 8 stable samples
    constant C_MAX       : positive := 250_000; -- Sample every 2.5ms (at 100MHz)

    -- ... rest of your signals ...
Why it's still skipping (The "Pulse" Check)
If you update those constants and it still skips, there is one other place to look: The Edge Detector. In your debounce code, you have:

VHDL
btnl_pressed <= debounced(2) and not(delayed(2));
This is a "Rising Edge Detector." It should only stay '1' for exactly one clock cycle (10ns).

Crucial Check: In your Top-Level, make sure you are using the clk (100MHz) for the counter, not the slow sig_en. If the counter is running on a slow clock, that "one-cycle pulse" might actually last long enough to be counted twice.

Summary of the Fix
Open debounce.vhd.

Change C_MAX to 250,000.

Change C_SHIFT_LEN to 8.

Re-synthesize and generate bitstream.

Mechanical buttons are messy! 20ms-40ms is the standard "waiting period" to make sure a human finger has finished its "bouncing" on the metal contact. Try those values and the DP should move exactly one step per click.

okay, we forgot that, how can we make the program only work for numbers 0-9, and not use the hexadecimal ones?

To restrict the system to decimal numbers (0−9), you have two choices: either prevent the "illegal" numbers from being saved in the register, or change how the switches are interpreted.

The cleanest and most user-friendly way is to modify the Registr module. We can add a "guard" that only allows the write operation to happen if the switches are currently showing a value less than or equal to 9.

1. Updating the Registr Module
We will modify the elsif write_en = '1' block. By adding a check for unsigned(sw_in) <= 9, the safe will simply "ignore" the button press if the user has switches set to A, B, C, D, E, or F.

VHDL
-- Add this library at the top if not already there
use IEEE.NUMERIC_STD.ALL;

-- Inside your p_register_write process:
elsif write_en = '1' then
    -- Check if the switch value is a valid decimal (0-9)
    if (unsigned(sw_in) <= 9) then 
        case idx_pos is
            when "00"   => sig_reg0 <= sw_in;
            when "01"   => sig_reg1 <= sw_in;
            when "10"   => sig_reg2 <= sw_in;
            when "11"   => sig_reg3 <= sw_in;
            when others => null;
        end case;
    else
