we got errors, like sw_in is not declared in display driver, and that idx_pos has no actual or default value

Ah, the classic VHDL "missing handshake" errors! These happen because we changed the Entity (the interface) of the display_driver, but the Top-Level (the wrapper) still thinks it's looking at the old version.

Here is why those specific errors are happening and how to clear them:

1. "sw_in is not declared in display_driver"
This happens if you added sw_in to the Port Map (the connection) in the Top-Level, but forgot to update the Component Declaration at the top of the architecture. In VHDL, you have to define the "blueprint" (component) and the "actual part" (entity) identically.

2. "idx_pos has no actual or default value"
This usually means there is a mismatch in the port order or a missing comma in the port map. If VHDL gets confused by the order of signals, it thinks you skipped a required input.

The Fix: Synchronizing the Top-Level
Open your Digital_Safe.vhd (Top-Level) and ensure these two sections match exactly:

Part A: The Component Declaration
Scroll to the top of your architecture. Make sure the component has the sw_in line:

VHDL
    component display_driver is
        Port ( 
            clk, rst : in  STD_LOGIC;
            data_in  : in  STD_LOGIC_VECTOR (15 downto 0);
            sw_in    : in  STD_LOGIC_VECTOR (3 downto 0); -- <--- MUST BE HERE
            idx_pos  : in  STD_LOGIC_VECTOR (1 downto 0);
            seg      : out STD_LOGIC_VECTOR (6 downto 0);
            anode    : out STD_LOGIC_VECTOR (3 downto 0);
            dp       : out STD_LOGIC
        );
    end component;
Part B: The Port Map
Scroll down to inst_display. Make sure every signal is linked correctly:

VHDL
    inst_display: display_driver
        port map (
            clk      => clk,
            rst      => btnu,
            data_in  => s_full_code,
            sw_in    => sw,           -- Link to physical switches
            idx_pos  => s_slot_idx,   -- Link to navigation counter
            seg      => seg,
            anode    => s_an_4,
            dp       => dp
        );
One more thing to check...
If you still get the error, check the display_driver.vhd file itself.

Ensure the entity display_driver also has sw_in : in STD_LOGIC_VECTOR (3 downto 0);.

Save all files! Sometimes Vivado/ISE uses an old cached version of a file if you haven't hit "Save All" before hitting "Synthesize."

Common VHDL Trap: If you have sw_in as the last item in your Entity Port list, make sure it doesn't have a semicolon ; before the closing parenthesis ).

Example:
idx_pos : in STD_LOGIC_VECTOR (1 downto 0); <--- Has semicolon
dp : out STD_LOGIC <--- No semicolon (it's the last one)

